\begin{align*}
k_1&=\frac{-(6-m)-\sqrt{(6-m)^2+4(m+1)}}{2}\\
&=\frac{-(6-m)-\sqrt{m^2-8m+40}}{2}
\end{align*} and
\begin{align*}
k_2&=\frac{-(6-m)+\sqrt{(6-m)^2+4(m+1)}}{2}\\
&=\frac{-(6-m)+\sqrt{m^2-8m+40}}{2}\\
\end{align*} The distance between the points of intersection is: $$\begin{array}{ cl@{\hspace{1 ern}}ll}
|k_1-k_2|&=&\left |\frac{-(6-m)-\sqrt{m^2-8m+40}}{2}-\frac{-(6-m)+\sqrt{m^2-8m+40}}{2} \right |\\
&=&\left |\frac{-2\sqrt{m^2-8m+40}}{2} \right |\\
&=&|\sqrt{m^2-8m+40}|\\
\end{array}$$ Since the distance is $5$, $|\sqrt{m^2-8m+40}|=5$ and $m^2-8m+40=25$, then $m^2-8m+15=0$, and $(m-3)(m-5)=0$, so $m=3$ or $m=5$. If $m=3$, then $b=3$ and the equation of the line is $y=3x+3$. If $m=5$, then $b=-1$ and the equation of the line is $y=5x-1$. In conclusion, the equation of the line is $\boxed{y=3x+3}$ or $y=5x-1}$</answer>

